<LEADPARA>  Queen Elizabeth II, one of the world's richest women, pays no income tax. A
large majority of Britons think that's wrong, by one poll, and legislator
Simon Hughes is trying to do something about it.;    Hughes planned to present
a bill in the House of Commons today proposing that the queen pay income taxes
levied on all of her considerable assets, the exact value of which are kept
secret.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  QUEEN FACES TAX DEBATE
LEGISLATION WOULD FORCE HER TO PAY FEE ON
INCOME  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The Liberal Democrat's bill apparently stands no chance of becoming law
because both the Conservative government and the leadership of the opposition
<ORGANIZATION>Labor Party</ORGANIZATION> oppose it. They don't want to upset the monarchy or its
supporters.;    But the bill was expected to test parliamentary opinion on an
issue that has attracted much media attention.;    Conservative legislator
<PERSON>Anthony Beaumont-Dark</PERSON>, Labor legislator <PERSON>Brian Wilson</PERSON> and <PERSON>Hughes</PERSON> called in an
Independent Television program last week for the queen to pay taxes.;    The
rest of the royal family pays taxes.;    An opinion poll published by The
Independent on <DATE>Sunday</DATE> some weeks ago said <PERCENT>79 percent</PERCENT> of 1,090 Britons
questioned in <DATE>February</DATE> thought the queen should be taxed. The newspaper gave
no margin of error.;    Hughes estimates the <ORGANIZATION>Treasury</ORGANIZATION> could raise <MONEY>$11.2
million</MONEY> a year if the queen's income were taxed. He told the <ORGANIZATION>British
Broadcasting Corp.</ORGANIZATION> in a radio program <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>: "It is completely unfair that
the richest woman in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> should be exempt.";    <ORGANIZATION>Buckingham Palace</ORGANIZATION>
officials say the queen's fortune, which includes jewel and art collections,
race horses and real estate, is a private matter. Media estimates of its worth
vary widely.;    The British magazine Harpers and Queen in <DATE>February</DATE> named her
as the world's richest woman with assets of <MONEY>$10.5 billion</MONEY>. Fortune magazine
estimated the value of her investments alone at the end of the <DATE>1980s</DATE> at <MONEY>$3.5
billion.</MONEY>;    But the Independent said <DATE>today</DATE> it was a myth that she has
billions invested. It said palace officials were content with estimates
valuing her investments at <MONEY>$192 million.</MONEY>;    A survey by the Independent today
said that elsewhere in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, the Spanish, Swedish, Belgian and Dutch royal
families all pay tax on their private fortunes. It said only the Norwegian and
Danish monarchies do not pay taxes, but they are among the royal families on
the continent with the fewest holdings.;    The queen's defenders say she
already contributes to the Exchequer through her <PERSON>Crown Estates</PERSON>, which include
farmland and <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> real estate, officially valued at nearly <MONEY>$3.8 billion</MONEY> last
year.  </TEXT>
