photo.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British actress <PERSON>Jane Seymour</PERSON> says she found
much to admire in <PERSON>Wallis Simpson</PERSON>, the American divorcee who became
the duchess of <LOCATION>Windsor</LOCATION>, the woman the English loved to hate.
   ``She was the woman who stole their king,'' says <PERSON>Seymour</PERSON>, who
portrays <PERSON>Simpson</PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION>CBS</ORGANIZATION> movie, ``The Woman He Loved.''
   ``They hated her. She was a naive American who didn't understand
the monarchy or how it worked or what it stood for. She thought
<PERSON>David</PERSON> could make her his queen.''
   Instead, <PERSON>David</PERSON>, already <PERSON>King Edward VIII</PERSON> but not yet crowned,
was forced to abdicate in <DATE>1936</DATE> to marry <LOCATION>Wallis</LOCATION>. They became the
duke and duchess of <LOCATION>Windsor</LOCATION> and lived the rest of their lives in
exile.
   The two-hour movie, which <ORGANIZATION>CBS</ORGANIZATION> will televise on <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, also
stars <PERSON>Anthony Andrews</PERSON> as <PERSON>David</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Olivia de Havilland</LOCATION> as <PERSON>Wallis</PERSON>' <PERSON>Aunt
Bessie</PERSON>, <PERSON>Julie Harris</PERSON> as her mother, <PERSON>Lucy Gutteridge</PERSON> as another
woman who saw herself as <PERSON>David</PERSON>'s queen, <PERSON>Robert Hardy</PERSON> as <ORGANIZATION>Winston
Churchill</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Phyllis Calvert</PERSON> as Queen <PERSON>Mary</PERSON>.
   ``I've never heard anyone say a good word about her,'' <PERSON>Seymour</PERSON>
says. ``Other than that, she gave great dinner parties. But I liked
her. She had a sense of humor, a straightforwardness. She was
definitely attentive to her husband and, although she was no
beauty, she had style and elegance. I certainly wouldn't trust her
with my husband.
   ``It's boring to play a perfect person. But to play a woman who
was not liked and to find something about her that is likeable is
fascinating.''
   Seymour says she saw <PERSON>David</PERSON> as a weak man who never really wanted
to be king. <PERSON>Wallis Simpson</PERSON> fulfilled some of his needs.
   ``Rumor has it that <PERSON>Wallis</PERSON> learned to do sexual tricks when she
lived in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>,'' she says. ``The king had a few problems in that
area and she fixed them.''
   When <PERSON>Wallis</PERSON> first met <PERSON>David</PERSON>, he was the prince of <LOCATION>Wales</LOCATION> and she
was married to American businessman <PERSON>Ernest Simpson</PERSON>. The flirtation
turned to romance, and <PERSON>Simpson</PERSON>'s marriage to divorce. Her plan was
to marry <PERSON>David</PERSON> and become queen, but the British prime minister and
royal family forbade his marriage as king to a twice-divorced woman.
   ``The Woman He Loved'' takes a different and less political
approach than the British-made miniseries ``Edward and <PERSON>Mrs.
Simpson</PERSON>,'' which ran on <ORGANIZATION>PBS</ORGANIZATION> several years ago.
   English newspapers became heavily involved with the making of
``The Woman He Loved'' and <PERSON>Seymour</PERSON> says one paper seemed to give
royal status to her role-playing. The Times published <PERSON>Seymour</PERSON>'s
picture as the duchess at <ORGANIZATION>David</ORGANIZATION>'s funeral. It went on the <ORGANIZATION>Court
Circular Page</ORGANIZATION>, a serious chronicle of royal events.
   ``I tried to play her in various shades of gray,'' <PERSON>Seymour</PERSON> says.
``I play her the way I believe she was thinking at the time. She
was manipulating things. She had a great plan and it didn't work. I
purposely don't play her sympathetically.''
   Parts of the movie were filmed in western <LOCATION>England</LOCATION>, where <PERSON>Seymour</PERSON>
owns a 15th-century estate outside the old Roman spa city of Bath.
She stayed at her home, <ORGANIZATION>St. Catherine's Court</ORGANIZATION>, during that time.
   Seymour divides her time between <LOCATION>England</LOCATION>, where she is still a
citizen, and this country, where she has lived for the past 10
years. She and her husband, American businessman <PERSON>David Flynn</PERSON>, have
two children, <PERSON>Katie</PERSON>, 5, born here, and <PERSON>Sean</PERSON>, 2, born in <LOCATION>England</LOCATION>.
   She works mostly in American television and films, having shed
her English accent in order to play American roles.
   Seymour was on her way to <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> to play opera star <PERSON>Maria Callas</PERSON>
in the <ORGANIZATION>ABC</ORGANIZATION> miniseries ``Onassis: The Richest Man in the World.''
The four-hour miniseries, which tells of the romance between <PERSON>Callas</PERSON>
and Greek magnate <PERSON>Aristotle Onassis</PERSON> (<PERSON>Raul Julia</PERSON>), will be televised
in early <DATE>May</DATE>.
   She has already completed her role as <PERSON>Natalie Jastrow Henry</PERSON> in
``War and Remembrance,'' the 30-hour miniseries being readied for
<ORGANIZATION>ABC</ORGANIZATION> next season. So far she has starred in 10 American miniseries.
   ``This seems to be my `duchess and diva' period,'' she says with
a laugh. ``I seem to be getting some great roles now. It's very
exciting. I'm like a chameleon, changing the way I look, the way I
sound, the kind of roles I play.''
   She took over the role played by <PERSON>Ali MacGraw</PERSON> in ``The Winds of
War,'' the first of author <PERSON>Herman Wouk</PERSON>'s two massive novels on
World War II.
   For her role as <PERSON>Maria Callas</PERSON> she had to learn to sing several
arias. She also worked with dialect coach <PERSON>Robert Easton</PERSON> for her
roles as <PERSON>Wallis Simpson</PERSON> and <PERSON>Maria Callas</PERSON>.
   Next, she goes to <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> for a role in the <ORGANIZATION>CBS</ORGANIZATION> miniseries ``Jack
the Ripper.'' She plays the romantic interest to <PERSON>Michael Caine</PERSON>, who
stars as <LOCATION>Scotland</LOCATION> Yard Inspector <PERSON>Frederick Abberline</PERSON>. <PERSON>Armand
Assante</PERSON> also stars as an American actor playing ``Dr. Jekyll and
<PERSON>Mr. Hyde</PERSON>'' on the <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> stage at the time of <PERSON>Jack the Ripper</PERSON>'s
reign of terror.
</TEXT>
