<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II joined 400th anniversary
celebrations <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> of the first Welsh-language <LOCATION>Bible</LOCATION>, a
translation ordered by her namesake, <PERSON>Elizabeth I.</PERSON>
   The queen participated in a bilingual service at <ORGANIZATION>Westminster
Abbey</ORGANIZATION> in honor of the <DATE>1588</DATE> translation as well as an upcoming Bible
which has taken Welsh scholars 26 years to complete.
   She accepted a copy of the <DATE>1588</DATE> Bible and thanked God ``for the
blessing that his book has been for the Welsh people,'' as 1,500
Welsh and English dignitaries looked on.
   Welsh is still taught in schools in <LOCATION>Wales</LOCATION> but the number of
native speakers has declined to <PERCENT>64 percent</PERCENT> in Welsh-speaking areas
this year from <PERCENT>71.3 percent</PERCENT> in <DATE>1981</DATE>, a recent survey has found.
   Wales was brought under English rule in <DATE>1282</DATE> by King Edward I and
united with <LOCATION>England</LOCATION> in <DATE>1536</DATE>.
</TEXT>
