MAORI RIGHTS CAMPAIGNERS HECKLE QUEEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WAITANGI, New Zealand 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A young woman threw a T-shirt at <ORGANIZATION>Queen Elizabeth II</ORGANIZATION> today and radicals 
campaigning for Maori rights heckled the British monarch during anniversary 
celebrations for the founding of modern <LOCATION>New Zealand</LOCATION>. 
</P>
<P>
The queen, who was accompanied by her husband, <PERSON>Prince Philip</PERSON>, appeared shaken, 
witnesses said. 
</P>
<P>
The woman, a member of <LOCATION>New Zealand</LOCATION>'s Maori minority, threw a black T-shirt 
after the queen disembarked from the royal barge that carried her to <LOCATION>Waitangi</LOCATION>, 
a village in the country's far north. 
</P>
<P>
Angry spectators seized the woman, aged about 17, dragged her from the crowd 
and handed her over to police. 
</P>
<P>
As the queen gave a speech marking the 150th anniversary of the <ORGANIZATION>Treaty of 
Waitangi</ORGANIZATION>, a pact between Maoris and British colonial authorities, a small group 
of radicals shouted "You already have everything! What more do you want, 
<PERSON>Elizabeth</PERSON>?" and "150 years of oppression!" 
</P></TEXT>
